In C++, there are several ways to create an array of integers, each suited for different situations. Below are the most common methods:

### 1. Static Arrays

A static array has a fixed size, which must be known at compile time.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int myArray[5]; // Declares an array of 5 integers.

    // Initialize array elements
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        myArray[i] = i * 2; // Example initialization
    }

    // Access array elements
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        std::cout << myArray[i] << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### 2. Dynamic Arrays

If you need an array where the size can be determined at runtime, you can allocate it dynamically.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int size = 5; // This can be set at runtime
    int* myArray = new int[size];

    // Initialize array elements
    for(int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        myArray[i] = i * 2; // Example initialization
    }

    // Access array elements
    for(int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        std::cout << myArray[i] << std::endl;
    }

    delete[] myArray; // Remember to free the allocated memory

    return 0;
}
```

### 3. Using `std::vector`

`std::vector` is a part of the C++ Standard Template Library (STL) and provides a more flexible and high-level way to deal with arrays that can dynamically resize.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> myVector = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}; // Initialize a vector

    // Add elements
    myVector.push_back(6); // myVector now contains 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6

    // Access elements
    for(int i = 0; i < myVector.size(); i++) {
        std::cout << myVector[i] << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### 4. `std::array` (since C++11)

`std::array` is a container that encapsulates fixed size arrays. It can be used if you know the size of the array at compile time and want the benefits of modern container classes, like iterators.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <array>

int main() {
    std::array<int, 5> myArray = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}; // Declare and initialize

    // Access elements
    for(int i = 0; i < myArray.size(); i++) {
        std::cout << myArray[i] << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Choosing the Right Type

- Use static arrays or `std::array` when you know the size at compile time and it does not change.
- Use `std::vector` when you need a container that can change size at runtime.
- Dynamic raw arrays (`new[]` and `delete[]`) are less commonly used due to their complexity and the higher risk of memory leaks or errors, so prefer `std::vector` or `std::array` for most cases.

